did.abstract: Founded in 1982 by Jeanette Ingberman and Papo Colo, Exit Art was an interdisciplinary cultural center in New York City that presented innovative exhibitions, films and performances that reflected a commitment to contemporary issues and ideas. The Exit Art Archive includes exhibition administrative files, artist research and records, events promotional and press materials, correspondence, ephemera, photographic elements, video, audio, and data storage components.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The first three series are available for research while the rest of the collection remains in process. This collection is arranged into the following series:

Series I: Exhibition Files includes documentation of all aspects of creating and executing exhibitions, including research, artist profiles, correspondence, financial records, promotional and press materials. This series is arranged chronologically by exhibition opening date.

Series II: Jeanette Ingberman Files is arranged into three subseries that separate exhibition press pack materials, personal correspondence and ephemera, and Exit Art administrative components. These materials are arranged chronologically, then alphabetically by record type.

Subseries A: Jeanette Ingberman Exhibition Files
Subseries B: Jeanette Ingberman Personal Files
Subseries C: Jeanette Ingberman Administrative Files
Series III: Potential Exhibitions consists of unrealized exhibitions. Record types include research and artist profiles. This series is arranged alphabetically by project title.

bioghist.head: Historical Note
bioghist.p: Founded by director Jeanette Ingberman and artist Papo Colo as an alternative art space in 1982, Exit Art was an interdisciplinary cultural center that presented innovative exhibitions, films and performances that reflected a commitment to contemporary issues and ideas. With a substantial reputation for curatorial innovation and depth of programming in diverse media, Exit Art was always changing.

During its first decade, Exit Art presented artists whose work challenged notions of race, ethnicity, gender, sexuality, and equality. It mounted a series of mid-career retrospectives which helped to bring wider public attention and critical acclaim to artists who are now firmly established, including Jimmie Durham, Willie Birch, Krzysztof Wodiczko, Tehching Hsieh, Martin Wong, Adrian Piper, David Wojnarowicz and David Hammons.

In its second decade, Exit Art identified a new generation of young, emerging artists with diverse backgrounds and organized a series of exhibitions, launching the careers of artists such as Shirin Neshat, Fred Tomaselli, Nicole Eisenman, Roxy Paine, Patty Chang, Julie Mehretu, Sue DeBeer, Rirkrit Tiravanija and Chakaia Booker. Fever (1992), the first exhibition in the series, was named one of the ten most important shows of the decade by Peter Plagens in Newsweek.

In its final decade, Exit Art became a leading voice in experimental art, producing exhibitions that illuminated the pressing issues of its time while supporting artists whose works reflected cultural transformations. By 2012, its 30th and final year, Exit Art had organized more than 200 exhibitions, events, festivals and programs featuring more than 2,500 artists.
Biographical information provided by the Exit Art website.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: Series I, II and II are open to researchers. Appointments are necessary for the use of manuscript and archival collections. Other series have not been processed and are not available.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: Collection use is subject to all copyright laws. Permission to publish materials must be obtained in writing from the Director of Fales Library and Special Collections. Please contact fales.library@nyu.edu. or call 212 998 2596.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p:
Published citations should take the following form:
Identification of item, date (if known); Exit Art Archive; MSS 343; box number; folder number; Fales Library and Special Collections, New York University Libraries.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: The Exit Art Archive consists of records documenting all aspects of the exhibition process, from conception to execution, to reception. This collection includes administrative files, artist profiles and research, ephemera, financial documents, promotional and press materials, professional and personal correspondence, photographic elements, and project proposals, in addition to video, audio, and data storage components.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: The Exit Art Archives was donated to NYU's Fales Library and Special Collections in 2012.
